ltural work such figures perform, locating lesbian desire in American literary history and engaging issues of genre and narrative, social formations such as the rhetoric of the "New Woman," and intersections of racism, sexism, and homophobia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited States. 0aLesbians in literature. 0aLesbianszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aLesbians' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited States. 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171875540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501718755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501718755/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles